---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import "../../styles/global.css";
---

<Layout
  title="FAQ - New Zealand Salary & Tax Questions | TakeHomePay.nz"
  description="Frequently asked questions about New Zealand salary calculations, PAYE tax, ACC levy, KiwiSaver contributions, student loan repayments, and more."
  canonical="/faq/"
>
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-primary to-primary-light py-12">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 text-center text-white">
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold mb-4 text-white">Frequently Asked Questions</h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-white/90">Common questions about New Zealand salary, tax, and deductions.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-12 sm:py-16">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="space-y-8">

        <div class="border border-border rounded-xl p-6">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">What is PAYE in New Zealand?</h2>
          <p class="text-text leading-relaxed">PAYE stands for Pay As You Earn. It is the system used by Inland Revenue (IRD) to collect income tax from employees in New Zealand. Your employer deducts PAYE tax from your wages or salary each pay period and sends it directly to IRD on your behalf. The amount deducted depends on your income level and the tax code you have provided to your employer. New Zealand uses a progressive tax system with five income brackets ranging from 10.5% to 39%.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-border rounded-xl p-6">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">How many PAYE tax brackets are there in NZ?</h2>
          <p class="text-text leading-relaxed">There are five PAYE income tax brackets for the 2025-2026 tax year: 10.5% on income up to $15,600; 17.5% on income from $15,601 to $53,500; 30% on income from $53,501 to $78,100; 33% on income from $78,101 to $180,000; and 39% on income above $180,000. These brackets are progressive, meaning each rate only applies to the income within that particular range, not your entire income.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-border rounded-xl p-6">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">What is the ACC Earner's Levy?</h2>
          <p class="text-text leading-relaxed">The ACC (Accident Compensation Corporation) Earner's Levy is a contribution that all New Zealand employees pay to fund the ACC scheme, which provides no-fault personal injury cover. For 2025-2026, the levy is 1.60% of your earnings, capped at earnings of approximately $142,283 per year. This means the maximum annual ACC Earner's Levy is around $2,276.53 regardless of how much more you earn above the cap.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-border rounded-xl p-6">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">What KiwiSaver rate should I choose?</h2>
          <p class="text-text leading-relaxed">KiwiSaver offers employee contribution rates of 3%, 4%, 6%, 8%, or 10% of your gross pay. The right rate depends on your financial situation. A higher rate means more savings for retirement but less take home pay now. Most financial advisors suggest contributing at least enough to maximise your employer's matching contribution (3% minimum). If you can afford it, higher contributions benefit from compound growth over time. Remember, your employer is required to contribute a minimum of 3% regardless of your chosen rate.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-border rounded-xl p-6">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">How are student loan repayments calculated?</h2>
          <p class="text-text leading-relaxed">Student loan repayments are calculated at 12% on every dollar you earn above the annual repayment threshold of $22,828 (approximately $439 per week). Repayments are deducted automatically by your employer through the PAYE system. Student loans are interest-free for borrowers who remain in New Zealand, but interest may apply if you move overseas. Your repayment obligation continues until the loan is fully repaid.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-border rounded-xl p-6">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">What is the Independent Earner Tax Credit (IETC)?</h2>
          <p class="text-text leading-relaxed">The IETC is a tax credit of up to $520 per year available to NZ tax residents earning between $24,000 and $48,000 annually. You must not receive any income-tested benefits, Working for Families tax credits, or NZ Superannuation. The full credit applies for incomes between $24,000 and $44,000. Between $44,000 and $48,000, it reduces by 13 cents for each dollar over $44,000. To claim the IETC, you need to use the "ME" or "MESL" tax code.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-border rounded-xl p-6">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">What is the NZ minimum wage in 2025-2026?</h2>
          <p class="text-text leading-relaxed">The adult minimum wage in New Zealand is $23.15 per hour as of 1 April 2025. For a full-time employee working 40 hours per week, this equates to approximately $48,152 per year before tax. The minimum wage is reviewed annually by the government and typically adjusted each April. Separate (lower) rates may apply for starting-out and training workers.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-border rounded-xl p-6">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">Is this calculator accurate?</h2>
          <p class="text-text leading-relaxed">Our calculator uses the official PAYE tax brackets, ACC Earner's Levy rate, KiwiSaver rates, and student loan repayment thresholds published by IRD for the 2025-2026 tax year. However, individual circumstances may vary. The calculator does not account for secondary employment income, investment income, other tax credits, or complex tax situations. For personalised tax advice, please consult a qualified accountant or tax advisor, or contact IRD directly.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-border rounded-xl p-6">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">What is the NZ tax year?</h2>
          <p class="text-text leading-relaxed">The New Zealand tax year runs from 1 April to 31 March. The current 2025-2026 tax year began on 1 April 2025 and ends on 31 March 2026. Income tax assessments, tax credits, and most rate changes are aligned to the tax year cycle. IRD typically processes automatic income tax assessments for individuals within a few months after the end of each tax year.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-border rounded-xl p-6">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">Can I opt out of KiwiSaver?</h2>
          <p class="text-text leading-relaxed">New employees are automatically enrolled in KiwiSaver when they start a new job. You can opt out within the first 2 to 8 weeks of starting employment. After this opt-out window, you can apply for a savings suspension (currently up to 12 months at a time) or, in certain hardship circumstances, apply for a withdrawal. Once you are a member, you cannot permanently leave the scheme, but you can take a contributions holiday. If you opt out, your employer does not need to make employer contributions.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

